clinicalDescription: Overview: Eclampsia is the convulsive manifestation of preeclampsia and is described as new-onset, generalized, tonic-clonic seizures or coma in a woman with preeclampsia (including HELLP syndrome - hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, low platelets). Many times, a woman may develop eclampsia with only an observation of gestational hypertension and no formal diagnosis of preeclampsia. Presentation: generalized tonic clonic seizures while pregnant, occassionally without any prior signs/symptoms. Commonly occurs between 20 to 30 weeks of pregnancy. Plan: Clinical diagnosis. Evaluate the cause. Prevent maternal hypoxemia. Prognosis:
